{"highlight_concerns": {"First of all—take a breath. Three hours feels huge when you’re anxious, but in real life it’s actually not that long. People get busy, tired, distracted, or forget to reply all the time.


Texting “are you mad at me?” isn’t cringe, but it can sometimes make things more awkward if they weren’t mad in the first place. It can put pressure on them or make it seem like something is wrong when it might not be.": ["b72949bd-a12d-41b2-a849-56fee1888309"], "Our brains are really good at jumping to “they hate me” when the reality is usually “they’re busy.”": ["b72949bd-a12d-41b2-a849-56fee1888309", "207fa58d-838a-4753-8a9c-98ea70bceb0b"], "Do you think something specific happened that might’ve upset them, or is this just anxiety talking?": ["b72949bd-a12d-41b2-a849-56fee1888309", "207fa58d-838a-4753-8a9c-98ea70bceb0b", "8ca7efa7-6acb-490e-957f-6a7812bab275"]}, "highlight_ratings": {"First of all—take a breath. Three hours feels huge when you’re anxious, but in real life it’s actually not that long. People get busy, tired, distracted, or forget to reply all the time.


Texting “are you mad at me?” isn’t cringe, but it can sometimes make things more awkward if they weren’t mad in the first place. It can put pressure on them or make it seem like something is wrong when it might not be.": 4, "Our brains are really good at jumping to “they hate me” when the reality is usually “they’re busy.”": 3, "Do you think something specific happened that might’ve upset them, or is this just anxiety talking?": 3}}

